amics of Colombian immigration to metropolitan Miami. More notably, placed in this context, the book discusses the creative work and media personas of talented Colombian artists Shakira, Andrea Echeverri of Aterciopelados, and Carlos Vives. In her examination of the transnational figures and music that illuminate the recent shifts in the meanings attached to Colombian identity both in the United States and Latin America, Cepeda argues that music is a powerful arbitrator of memory and transnational identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aIdentity (Psychology) and mass media. 0aMusic tradezFloridazMiami. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPopular musiczColombiaxHistory and criticism. 0aPopular musiczFloridazMiamixHistory and criticism. 4aColombian. 4aImagiNation. 4aMiami. 4aMusical. 4acrisis. 4adynamics. 4aeconomic. 4aimmigration. 4ametropolitan. 4aongoing. 4aoverview. 4apolitical. 4aprovides. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814772904423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814772904.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK